1
00:02:21,500 --> 00:02:23,293
This is the story...

2
00:02:23,293 --> 00:02:25,794
of how I almost lived
my entire adult life...

3
00:02:25,794 --> 00:02:27,797
in a functional coma...

4
00:02:27,797 --> 00:02:30,799
instead of becoming the writer
I always dreamed I'd be...

5
00:02:30,799 --> 00:02:33,802
like Sylvia Plath, only happy.

6
00:02:33,802 --> 00:02:36,305
To be a writer
was my childhood dream...

7
00:02:36,305 --> 00:02:39,307
but like my childhood,
the dream was sweet...

8
00:02:39,307 --> 00:02:40,725
but mostly it was short.

9
00:02:40,725 --> 00:02:43,269
My parents died
in a car accident...

10
00:02:43,269 --> 00:02:45,812
leaving my sister
and me orphans.

11
00:02:45,812 --> 00:02:48,107
My sister acted
like a brat at the funeral...

12
00:02:48,107 --> 00:02:49,983
setting a life-long pattern...

13
00:02:49,983 --> 00:02:52,986
of always doing and saying
whatever she felt.

14
00:02:54,862 --> 00:02:59,033
As for me, the next twelve years
were very lonely...

15
00:02:59,033 --> 00:03:00,326
until...

16
00:03:02,078 --> 00:03:04,871
With this ring,
I thee wed.

17
00:03:08,417 --> 00:03:12,420
His name was Harry Turner,
and we were in love.

18
00:03:12,420 --> 00:03:15,381
I thought everything
was going to be perfect...

19
00:03:15,381 --> 00:03:18,426
and it might have been,
except for one thing...

20
00:03:18,426 --> 00:03:21,387
Harry was already married
to someone else...

21
00:03:22,388 --> 00:03:24,430
his family.

22
00:03:24,430 --> 00:03:26,433
Harry joined
their medical practice...

23
00:03:26,433 --> 00:03:28,935
and although I had his hand
in holy matrimony...

24
00:03:28,935 --> 00:03:30,603
they had his shingle.

25
00:03:31,938 --> 00:03:35,400
Harry became a brilliant
gastroenterologist...

26
00:03:35,400 --> 00:03:38,277
who really knew his way
around an intestine.

27
00:03:38,277 --> 00:03:39,778
See this part here?

28
00:03:41,905 --> 00:03:43,990
To people on the outside...

29
00:03:43,990 --> 00:03:46,952
I'm sure it looked like
we had a happy life together...

30
00:03:46,952 --> 00:03:48,953
and for a while,
I thought we did, too.

31
00:03:48,953 --> 00:03:50,955
I mean, things
weren't exactly...

32
00:03:50,955 --> 00:03:53,373
the way I would
have liked them...

33
00:03:53,373 --> 00:03:54,958
but I learned
to make compromises...

34
00:03:54,958 --> 00:03:58,461
which is how we achieved
a balance in our marriage.

35
00:03:58,461 --> 00:04:00,422
The problem is...

36
00:04:00,422 --> 00:04:02,340
somewhere during
eight years of balancing...

37
00:04:02,340 --> 00:04:04,885
I stopped thinking
of myself as me.

38
00:04:04,885 --> 00:04:07,929
All I was was Harry's wife.

39
00:04:07,929 --> 00:04:09,388
Hi. How are you?

40
00:04:10,890 --> 00:04:14,601
We were one of those couples
who did everything together...

41
00:04:14,601 --> 00:04:16,437
except communicate.

42
00:04:39,415 --> 00:04:41,125
Good night, dear.

43
00:04:44,629 --> 00:04:47,672
You didn't want
to make love, did you?

44
00:04:47,672 --> 00:04:49,424
No, no. That's all right.

45
00:04:49,424 --> 00:04:50,884
Good.

46
00:04:50,884 --> 00:04:52,885
Sex wasn't everything,
but it was...

47
00:04:52,885 --> 00:04:55,889
one of the few things we did
without Harry's family.

48
00:04:55,889 --> 00:04:59,683
So when that began to fade,
I should have said something...

49
00:04:59,683 --> 00:05:01,393
but I didn't know how.

50
00:05:02,852 --> 00:05:04,355
Harry, I thought I'd make...

51
00:05:04,355 --> 00:05:07,524
a nice, big pot roast
for your family tonight...

52
00:05:07,524 --> 00:05:08,858
or turkey.

53
00:05:08,858 --> 00:05:10,026
What do you think?

54
00:05:11,528 --> 00:05:14,322
Harry, can you hear me?

55
00:05:15,865 --> 00:05:16,866
Hello?

56
00:05:16,866 --> 00:05:18,992
Come on in, Iris.

57
00:05:18,992 --> 00:05:20,702
Your front door was open.

58
00:05:20,702 --> 00:05:21,745
I'm sorry.

59
00:05:21,745 --> 00:05:23,371
You want some coffee?

60
00:05:23,371 --> 00:05:24,873
Please.

61
00:05:24,873 --> 00:05:26,834
Marjorie? Coffee.

62
00:05:27,917 --> 00:05:29,126
I'll need some milk with that.

63
00:05:29,126 --> 00:05:30,670
With milk.

64
00:05:30,670 --> 00:05:32,170
What's this?

65
00:05:32,170 --> 00:05:34,173
"We love you loads,
Uncle Charles."

66
00:05:34,173 --> 00:05:36,092
The kids made it themselves.

67
00:05:36,092 --> 00:05:38,093
How can they love him loads?

68
00:05:38,093 --> 00:05:40,095
He left for Costa Rica
before they were born.

69
00:05:40,095 --> 00:05:42,888
I think they're just proud
to have an uncle...

70
00:05:42,888 --> 00:05:44,891
that helps so many people.

71
00:05:44,891 --> 00:05:46,476
All doctors help people.

72
00:05:46,476 --> 00:05:48,894
Charles travels all over
the world helping people.

73
00:05:48,894 --> 00:05:51,105
I don't think all doctors
do that, Harry.

74
00:05:51,105 --> 00:05:52,480
Here you go.

75
00:05:52,480 --> 00:05:54,733
Just like you like it...
with one splash.

76
00:05:54,733 --> 00:05:56,569
Low-fat.

77
00:05:56,569 --> 00:05:59,487
There's no problem.
Low-fat.

78
00:05:59,487 --> 00:06:02,072
Anyway, the kids
can't wait to meet him.

79
00:06:02,072 --> 00:06:03,700
I can't, either.

80
00:06:03,700 --> 00:06:05,577
It's so weird having
a brother-in-law...

81
00:06:05,577 --> 00:06:07,119
that I don't even know.

82
00:06:07,119 --> 00:06:08,954
It's weirder having
a brother you don't know.

83
00:06:08,954 --> 00:06:11,081
What's that supposed to mean?

84
00:06:11,081 --> 00:06:14,543
My own brother sends me
one letter in fifteen years.

85
00:06:14,543 --> 00:06:16,919
When you're off winning
the Nobel Peace Prize...

86
00:06:16,919 --> 00:06:18,588
you can't be expected to write
a bunch of letters.

87
00:06:18,588 --> 00:06:20,256
Did Charles win
a Nobel Peace Prize?

88
00:06:20,256 --> 00:06:22,174
He didn't win.
He was just nominated.

89
00:06:22,174 --> 00:06:23,801
Why do you do this?

90
00:06:23,801 --> 00:06:26,137
Do you think he'll like me?

91
00:06:26,137 --> 00:06:29,431
Of course he'll like you.
You're Harry's wife.

92
00:06:29,431 --> 00:06:30,765
Here you go. Low-fat.

93
00:06:30,765 --> 00:06:34,436
Too late. Gotta go.
Got a C-section at 9:00.

94
00:06:34,436 --> 00:06:37,438
And I've got a polyp at 9:30.

95
00:06:43,444 --> 00:06:45,446
Hiya, doll.
How's my sweetheart?

96
00:06:45,446 --> 00:06:47,947
Tired. Haven't seen you
in a while, Nick.

97
00:06:47,947 --> 00:06:49,449
You been busy?

98
00:06:49,449 --> 00:06:50,950
Yeah. Busy, busy, busy.

99
00:06:50,950 --> 00:06:52,952
Having lunch
with my brother today.

100
00:06:52,952 --> 00:06:54,454
He's here.

101
00:06:54,454 --> 00:06:55,622
Good.

102
00:06:55,622 --> 00:06:57,122
How's the fish fry?

103
00:06:57,122 --> 00:06:58,916
I wouldn't eat it, honey.

104
00:07:00,918 --> 00:07:03,378
Hey, Wilbur!

105
00:07:03,378 --> 00:07:05,005
I hear the fish fry
is no good...

106
00:07:05,005 --> 00:07:07,799
but I got a feeling
about the meat loaf.

107
00:07:09,926 --> 00:07:11,635
Your landlord called me today.

108
00:07:11,635 --> 00:07:14,263
You haven't paid your rent
in four months.

109
00:07:14,263 --> 00:07:16,848
Your landlord says
you owe $1,200 back rent.

110
00:07:16,848 --> 00:07:18,308
I know.

111
00:07:18,308 --> 00:07:20,477
And I'm going to go
over to his office...

112
00:07:20,477 --> 00:07:22,020
after this lunch...

113
00:07:22,020 --> 00:07:23,980
and pay him part
of what I owe him...

114
00:07:23,980 --> 00:07:25,816
as a good faith kind of thing.

115
00:07:25,816 --> 00:07:27,983
Good. How much you
going to give him?

116
00:07:27,983 --> 00:07:29,235
$200.

117
00:07:29,235 --> 00:07:31,654
Where are you going
to get the money?

118
00:07:31,654 --> 00:07:33,155
Can you loan me 200 bucks?

119
00:07:33,155 --> 00:07:36,324
No, just until I close this
big deal that I'm working on.

120
00:07:36,324 --> 00:07:37,659
All right, Nick, look...

121
00:07:37,659 --> 00:07:40,161
I'll tell you what
I'm going to do.

122
00:07:40,161 --> 00:07:42,455
I'm going to lend you
the whole $1,200.

123
00:07:42,455 --> 00:07:44,999
Oh, no, no. Wilbur,
I can't take that much!

124
00:07:44,999 --> 00:07:47,626
Nick, you know I'm up
for chief of police.

125
00:07:47,626 --> 00:07:49,711
I know.
I can't believe it.

126
00:07:49,711 --> 00:07:51,713
But this kind of thing...

127
00:07:51,713 --> 00:07:53,799
could really hurt
my chances, Nick.

128
00:07:53,799 --> 00:07:55,634
You know, my brother
getting evicted...

129
00:07:55,634 --> 00:07:57,343
for not paying his rent.

130
00:07:57,343 --> 00:07:59,095
Right.

131
00:07:59,095 --> 00:08:00,929
I'm under
a magnifying glass, Nick.

132
00:08:00,929 --> 00:08:02,849
I got to get appointed
by the mayor.

133
00:08:02,849 --> 00:08:05,351
You get to meet the mayor?

134
00:08:05,351 --> 00:08:08,562
It's all public.
You could blow this for me.

135
00:08:08,562 --> 00:08:11,314
You deserve
to be chief of police...

136
00:08:11,314 --> 00:08:15,318
and I'm going to do everything
I can do to help, and...

137
00:08:15,318 --> 00:08:18,112
because we're brothers, and...

138
00:08:19,321 --> 00:08:20,823
I love you.

139
00:08:20,823 --> 00:08:22,825
I love you,
I love you,

140
00:08:22,825 --> 00:08:24,702
I love you,
I love you!

141
00:08:25,910 --> 00:08:28,163
Yeah. You wanted to see me, Pat?

142
00:08:28,163 --> 00:08:30,039
Shut the door.

143
00:08:34,169 --> 00:08:36,837
You've been working for me
for three months today...

144
00:08:36,837 --> 00:08:39,339
and you haven't sold
one set of blinds.

145
00:08:39,339 --> 00:08:40,465
Can I sit down here?

146
00:08:40,465 --> 00:08:41,675
No.

147
00:08:43,594 --> 00:08:45,053
Face it, Nick...

148
00:08:46,304 --> 00:08:48,139
You're just not a salesman.

149
00:08:48,139 --> 00:08:50,433
Oh, Pat, don't say that.

150
00:08:50,433 --> 00:08:52,643
You're hurting me.

151
00:08:52,643 --> 00:08:54,145
I gotta let you go.

152
00:08:54,145 --> 00:08:55,937
No, Pat. No. Not yet!

153
00:08:55,937 --> 00:08:59,858
You see, I...
I've got an appointment here...

154
00:08:59,858 --> 00:09:02,027
and I'm going down now to...

155
00:09:02,027 --> 00:09:03,779
I'm going to the Sheraton.

156
00:09:03,779 --> 00:09:05,362
The Sheraton?

157
00:09:05,362 --> 00:09:08,699
Yeah. I am going to put
an A-1 Acme vertical blind...

158
00:09:08,699 --> 00:09:11,243
in every window in every room
in that hotel.

159
00:09:11,243 --> 00:09:12,787
But the Sheraton's got drapes.

160
00:09:14,747 --> 00:09:16,873
Exactly.

161
00:09:21,920 --> 00:09:23,922
Hi, J.

162
00:09:23,922 --> 00:09:25,422
Hi. What's wrong?

163
00:09:25,422 --> 00:09:28,926
Nothing. I just came by
to drop these off.

164
00:09:28,926 --> 00:09:30,594
Why?

165
00:09:30,594 --> 00:09:32,596
Because I thought
this would be...

166
00:09:32,596 --> 00:09:35,181
a real good opportunity
for you to think about...

167
00:09:35,181 --> 00:09:36,766
going to community college.

168
00:09:36,766 --> 00:09:38,768
What are you,
my career counsellor?

169
00:09:38,768 --> 00:09:40,937
No. I'm your sister.

170
00:09:40,937 --> 00:09:43,439
Jeanine, I just think...

171
00:09:43,439 --> 00:09:45,440
that you can do
better than this.

172
00:09:45,440 --> 00:09:47,526
I like fish.

173
00:09:47,526 --> 00:09:49,736
Of course you like fish, because
you don't have to have...

174
00:09:49,736 --> 00:09:51,238
a real relationship
with a fish.

175
00:09:51,238 --> 00:09:54,449
I think you are
very, very unhappy...

176
00:09:54,449 --> 00:09:56,367
and I'm glad we're
talking about it...

177
00:09:56,367 --> 00:09:59,371
because I think you have a lot
of feelings bottled up inside.

178
00:09:59,371 --> 00:10:00,955
What are you talking about?

179
00:10:00,955 --> 00:10:02,456
Does Harry go down on you?

180
00:10:04,416 --> 00:10:05,792
I didn't think so.

181
00:10:05,792 --> 00:10:08,002
Please do not
talk to me like this.

182
00:10:08,002 --> 00:10:11,756
I bet you've never come
even once in your life.

183
00:10:11,756 --> 00:10:14,466
You just... Get back here,
young lady.

184
00:10:14,466 --> 00:10:15,926
Listen to me.

185
00:10:15,926 --> 00:10:18,303
This is why you don't
have a relationship!

186
00:10:18,303 --> 00:10:19,763
What?

187
00:10:19,763 --> 00:10:22,349
This... that... because you are
so forward.

188
00:10:22,349 --> 00:10:24,392
I'm not forward.
I'm honest.

189
00:10:24,392 --> 00:10:25,935
Is that what you call it?

190
00:10:25,935 --> 00:10:29,480
Is that why you're single,
making minimum wage?

191
00:10:29,480 --> 00:10:31,858
I don't want a relationship.
I'm independent.

192
00:10:31,858 --> 00:10:33,484
And as a matter of fact...

193
00:10:33,484 --> 00:10:35,152
I have had
quite a few relationships.

194
00:10:35,152 --> 00:10:37,070
No. To qualify
as a relationship...

195
00:10:37,070 --> 00:10:39,031
it has to last
longer than 24 hours!

196
00:10:39,031 --> 00:10:41,867
At least I didn't marry
the first guy who felt me up.

197
00:10:41,867 --> 00:10:44,368
He isn't the first guy who...
I had some...

198
00:10:44,368 --> 00:10:46,454
Could you grab those, please?

199
00:10:53,002 --> 00:10:54,502
Do you love Harry?

200
00:10:54,502 --> 00:10:57,630
Yes, I love Harry.
He is my husband.

201
00:10:58,674 --> 00:11:01,176
Why don't you like him?

202
00:11:01,176 --> 00:11:02,635
I like him.

203
00:11:02,635 --> 00:11:05,637
It's just that his whole family
treats me like street scum.

204
00:11:05,637 --> 00:11:07,473
They have never used
that exact term.

205
00:11:07,473 --> 00:11:08,891
Ever since you met this guy...

206
00:11:08,891 --> 00:11:10,809
your life got wrapped up
into this neat little package.

207
00:11:10,809 --> 00:11:13,853
You even stopped writing.
You used to love to write.

208
00:11:13,853 --> 00:11:15,855
That was a long time ago.

209
00:11:15,855 --> 00:11:17,398
And I never was a real writer.

210
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:20,359
You wrote short stories.

211
00:11:20,359 --> 00:11:22,028
Those weren't short stories.
Those were novels.

212
00:11:22,028 --> 00:11:23,737
I just never finished them.

213
00:11:23,737 --> 00:11:27,199
You started them a lot,
and since you got married...

214
00:11:27,199 --> 00:11:28,950
you stopped even starting them.

215
00:11:28,950 --> 00:11:30,410
This is ridiculous.

216
00:11:30,410 --> 00:11:33,371
I know you were a virgin
when you got married.

217
00:11:36,582 --> 00:11:39,418
Don't you ever wonder
if Harry's doing it right?

218
00:11:39,418 --> 00:11:41,378
Harry is doing it fine!

219
00:11:41,378 --> 00:11:43,797
And even if he weren't,
it's none of your business.

220
00:11:43,797 --> 00:11:47,718
You know what you should do?
You should have an affair.

221
00:11:47,718 --> 00:11:48,968
What?

222
00:11:48,968 --> 00:11:51,179
Then at least you'd have
some frame of reference.

223
00:11:51,179 --> 00:11:52,889
Do you know something?

224
00:11:52,889 --> 00:11:55,057
I have spent
most of my life...

225
00:11:55,057 --> 00:11:57,226
pretending like
you are retarded...

226
00:11:57,226 --> 00:12:00,854
just so I can stand
being related to you!

227
00:12:11,364 --> 00:12:13,199
You dented your cheese.

228
00:12:21,373 --> 00:12:23,415
Is this checkout line closed?

229
00:12:23,415 --> 00:12:26,878
No. The cashier just went to get
my credit card approved.

230
00:12:26,878 --> 00:12:30,464
She's going to let you use
a credit card to buy just that?

231
00:12:30,464 --> 00:12:33,258
No. I'm buying one of those
fruit baskets over there.

232
00:12:33,258 --> 00:12:35,051
This goes with that.

233
00:12:36,553 --> 00:12:38,304
What do you think?

234
00:12:38,304 --> 00:12:40,557
People really like
those kind of things?

235
00:12:41,933 --> 00:12:43,642
I don't know.
I suppose so.

236
00:12:43,642 --> 00:12:44,893
Would you like it?

237
00:12:44,893 --> 00:12:48,856
I don't know!
Sorry.

238
00:12:48,856 --> 00:12:52,025
You could use your anger
in a more productive way.

239
00:12:54,068 --> 00:12:55,445
How's that?

240
00:12:55,445 --> 00:12:58,281
You could help me
write this card.

241
00:12:58,281 --> 00:13:00,450
It might calm you down.

242
00:13:03,827 --> 00:13:05,328
What's the present for?

243
00:13:05,328 --> 00:13:06,831
A party.

244
00:13:06,831 --> 00:13:09,332
But I'm having second thoughts
about going.

245
00:13:11,376 --> 00:13:13,794
OK. Everything's ready.
Your order's in.

246
00:13:15,296 --> 00:13:17,882
Let's see...
I got the address.

247
00:13:17,882 --> 00:13:20,384
They're making up your basket
in the back...

248
00:13:20,384 --> 00:13:22,844
and we'll send it out
as soon as it's done.

249
00:13:22,844 --> 00:13:24,804
OK. Thanks.

250
00:13:24,804 --> 00:13:26,348
You done with that card yet?

251
00:13:26,348 --> 00:13:29,476
Not yet.
I was just getting some help.

252
00:13:32,561 --> 00:13:34,855
What do you say?

253
00:13:34,855 --> 00:13:38,275
So then you don't really
want to go to this party?

254
00:13:38,275 --> 00:13:39,860
No, not really.

255
00:13:39,860 --> 00:13:41,487
I feel obligated, but...

256
00:13:44,363 --> 00:13:46,200
Tell them to start without you.

257
00:13:47,492 --> 00:13:48,618
OK.

258
00:13:53,371 --> 00:13:55,248
That way, you know...

259
00:13:56,751 --> 00:14:00,545
You could go late,
if you wanted to.

260
00:14:08,344 --> 00:14:10,346
Chardonnay.
